		<header>
			
			<h1>Shifting global demand for cocoa and corporate repositioning </h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 September 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, cocoa demand is declining in Europe but rapidly growing in Asia. While cocoa grindings are falling in the EU and Switzerland, reflecting declining retail sales, consumption in India has increased threefold in 7 years, while Chinese imports since January 2012 have risen by 101.8% in comparison with the same period in 2011. This rise in Asian demand is more than offsetting the decline in European demand, creating a tight market situation. Rabobank projects production in 2012/13 of around 4.1 million tonnes, with consumption of around 4.2 million tonnes, and a deficit of 89,000 tonnes.</p><p>Increasing Asian demand has both direct and indirect implications for African cocoa producing countries. Exports of West and Central African countries to China have increased substantially (+90.19% in Ghana, +533% in Côte d’Ivoire and +183.3% in Cameroon). Rising Asian demand for cocoa-based products has also stimulated investment by Western companies in order to secure future supplies of cocoa to meet rising Asian demand. This ranges from corporate initiatives to support skills development in the cocoa sector (e.g. investment of €0.8 million by Barry Callebaut in a cocoa excellence centre in Côte d’Ivoire) to investments to boost production among 35,000 cocoa farmers in Cameroon, Côte d’Ivoire and Nigeria, implemented under the auspices of the World Cocoa Foundation (WCF) with the support of the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation, the Sustainable Trade Initiative, and several WCF member companies. This forms part of much larger corporate and WFC initiatives to boost sustainable cocoa production.</p><p>Investments are also under way to increase local processing of cocoa beans. According to the International Cocoa Organization (ICCO), African grindings of beans will reach 1.68 million tonnes in 2011/12, while European grinding will amount to only 1.6 million tonnes. In Côte d’Ivoire, ‘the grind will rise 440,000 tonnes in 2011-12’, equivalent to 30% of production. According to web-based analysts <i>Agrimoney.com</i>, this is ‘ending decades of dominance by processing industries centred largely in Germany and around Amsterdam’.</p><p>This evolving situation has its origin in the ‘uncertainty of the global economic situation, combined with sluggish growth predictions and deteriorating processing margins’ on the European side, but also ‘moves by producing countries, encouraged by the World Bank, to raise grinding capacity, allowing them to reap themselves processing margins’. ICCO is also pressing producing countries such as Nigeria to expand processing and production of value-added cocoa product to meet growing local demand. According to <i>Agrimoney.com</i>, this in part ‘reflects a move by the Western chocolate producers “away from processing cocoa themselves to buying in processed cocoa product” as the basis for their confectionery’.</p><p>The move to grinding beans and expanded production of cocoa-based product could well be made easier with private investments such as that planned by Algerian company Cevital, which is to invest US$200 million in Côte d’Ivoire in land acquisition and a cocoa processing plant with a capacity of 100,000 to 150,000 tonnes.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
