				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Growing Asian markets offer opportunities for the establishment of joint ventures which enable ACP cocoa producers to move up the value chain. In the longer term, however, this may require ACP producer bodies to become more involved in downstream businesses, by taking a financial stake in major multinationals involved in chocolate and confectionery production, so as to secure a greater share of the value-added in meeting expanding Asian demand. This can be seen as the next stage, building on recent investments in value-added processing of cocoa in West Africa.</p><p>This provides a background to the current re-evaluation of the use of trade policy tools in the cocoa sector in West Africa, a number of which (particularly relating to export taxes) could be seen as contravening provisions of interim EPAs and which may as a consequence require redefinition or restructuring (see <i>Agritrade</i> Special Report ‘Cocoa sector reform in Côte d’Ivoire’, 2012, forthcoming).</p>
		</div>
		
